{"key":"processedPost-14039449","value":{"id":14039449,"first":14024492,"last":14039449,"when":1298872077,"utime":"02/28/11 07:47 AM","cleanedPost":"It's all about strain isolation.&nbsp; A rock on a petri dish indicates a sclerotia producing strain, just as a fruit growing on a petri dish indicates a fruiting strain.&nbsp; <br />I also don't recommend against cloning.&nbsp; The oyster strain I grow commercially, I cloned from the wild back in 2004 and am still using that exact culture after growing tens of thousands of pounds of mushrooms from it.&nbsp; What I recommend against is cloning from a later flush or cloning the largest fruit.&nbsp; In addition, a clone may or may not be an isolate.&nbsp; If it sectors, fruit each sector to determine the best one.<br />Don't confuse advice to save culture slants over cloning as saying cloning is bad.&nbsp; It's just that if you refrigerate and save a slant before you fruit the culture, you have saved younger cell lines which will perform better in the future.<br />RR"}}